        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>Graecoru[m] polyhistores tradunt magnifica; et sua quisq[ue] dilatat. Romanoru[m] historici amplissima tractant; 
                        et ipsa produnt utriusq[ue] partis arcana. Illi non minùs delectant pulchris narrationibus: hi magis conducunt seriis actionibus. 
                        Qua[e] et sibi ad gloriam illustrissima[e] videbantur; et posteris ad cognitionem, actionemq[ue] 
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>vtilissima[e]. 
                        Superiora quidem strenua, nec vllo modo contemnenda: sed hîc demu[m] emergit Romana seges, et illa egrégia[e] virtutis 
                        quasi propria magnitudo; digna, qua[e] communium rerum sensim potiatur. Iam enim orbis domina[m] quasi in cunis video; 
                        ac potiùs in virescenti aetate; quae subinde ausit fores mundi aperire.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The polyhistors of the Greeks transmit splendid stories and each of them amplifies his own material. The historians of the 
                Romans treat the greatest subjects and reveal the very mysteries of either good or bad times. The former entertain no less with their 
                charming stories, the latter are more useful through their earnest actions. These were also the most distinguished for them in 
                terms of honour, and most useful in terms of knowledge and action to posterity. The former were strong indeed and should 
                not in any way be disdained. But here at last arises the Roman crop, and that more or less exclusive greatness of their 
                extraordinary virtue, that deserves gradually to control all public affairs. For at this stage I see the mistress of the world, 
                who later dared to open the doors of the world, in her cradle, as it were, or more exactly, at an age of growth.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
